{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508188"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:03:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:03:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2735"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2735"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.06,0.21,0.56,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2735"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41807"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2735"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2735"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26758"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"3915"},{"type":"tags","id":"5908"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3520"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3536"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41807"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with three weeks of muscle weakness. Over this time, he has noticed increasing difficulty standing up from sitting down and walking up stairs, most notable first thing in the morning. He has had no recent illness. He has a medical history of COPD and hypertension. His medications include hydrochlorothiazide and terbutaline. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and drinks one to two standard drinks per night.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological assessment shows mildly reduced power of hip flexion and adduction. Reflexes are reduced, however improve following 15 seconds of maximal isometric contraction. There are no sensory abnormalities. Cranial nerve examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Myasthenia gravis","Guillain-Barr\u00e9 Syndrome","Polymyositis","Lambert-Eaton syndrome","Dermatomyositis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELambert-Eaton syndrome \u003C/strong\u003Eis an autoimmune disease of the neuromuscular junction. In around half of cases, it is a paraneoplastic syndrome and investigation for small-cell lung cancer is essential. Examination of Lambert-Eaton syndrome involves reduced power and reflexes which improve after muscle use. Autonomic dysfunction is often a component, with dry mouth, blurred vision and postural hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis allows differentiation from \u003Cstrong\u003Emyasthenia gravis\u003C/strong\u003E, also a disease of the neuromuscular junction, which involves fatiguable weakness and reflexes i.e. becomes worse with use. Additionally, myasthenia gravis is more likely to involve extraocular and bulbar weakness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGuillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E classically presents with ascending weakness and areflexia and may progress to involve respiratory muscles. In two thirds of cases it is preceded by gastrointestinal or upper respiratory infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolymyositis\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Edermatomyositis\u003C/strong\u003E come under the umbrella of idiopathic inflammatory myopathies and involve progressive proximal muscle weakness +/- tenderness. Reflexes will remain intact in both conditions. Dermatomyositis, as the name suggests, involves characteristic cutaneous features (e.g. Gottron papules, photosensitive poikiloderma). It may also occur as a paraneoplastic syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Lambert-Eaton syndrome is characterised by proximal muscle weakness and reduced reflexes which improve following muscle use."],"references":["Barohn RJ, Dimachkie MM, Jackson CE. A pattern recognition approach to patients with a suspected myopathy. Neurol Clin. 2014;32(3):569-vii. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4233647/#:~:text=Since%20many%20myopathies%20are%20inherited,X%2Dlinked%20patterns%20of%20transmission.","Gonzalez-Perez P, Torre M, Helgager J, Amato A. Proximal muscle weakness. Pract Neurol. 2019;19(4):321. Available at: https://pn.bmj.com/content/19/4/321"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26758"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2735"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26758"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-23T21:13:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-23T21:13:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2735"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41807"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"d